value: Sotheby's, 21st July 1933, Anonymous Sale, lot 169;  bought by the Barbizon Gallery, King Street, St James Square, from whom purchased by The Friends of the Fitzwilliam Museum

Bronze. The moulded base is cast in one with the group - it is hollow cast - with dark brown patina, polished. The lion is seated on its haunches, looking down at the snake that it has pinned to the ground with its right paw. Its towering massive head and mane is supported by its left front leg. The word ''Barye'' is stamped on the base.

summary_title: The Friends of the Fitzwilliam Museum

value: Date of original model 1838. Original model revised to include integrally-cast base c. 1845. Present model (with integral base) cast at an unknown date after 1845.

notes: Cf. A similar bronze with slight variations in Wadsworth Atheneum, Hartford, Conneticut, USA, p. 136

summary_title: Catalogue of European Sculpture in the Ashmolean Museum, 1540 to the present day

notes: Cf. Sotheby's, London, 26 November 1996, 19th and 20th Century Sculpture, pp. 18-9, lot 22 'A lion crushing a serpent'. H. 25.5 cm. by 35.5 cm. (Estimate 6-8,000; unsold). Reference is made to G.F. Benge, 'Lion crushing a Serpent', in Metamorphosis in Nineteenth Century Sculpture, 1975, pp. 89-106, and to pp. 119-123. The text of the lot cites Alfred du Musset, 'The Lion roars'. The serpent hisses. What rage is in that snarling mask, in that sideward gaze, in the bristling fur of its back.' What delicacy in that paw set upon the prey'...in describing this bronze.
Model no. A 52. Cf: cast illustrated on p. 176.
